{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5ed5972e-e049-4ffd-b14b-f5c9794fafeb","content":"The repository doesn't contain documentation on this topic, but I can answer from general .NET knowledge:\n\n### Recovering a macOS crash dump without `createdump`\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS defaults to `/cores`):\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/   # look for core.<pid> after a crash\n   ```\n\n3. **If `/cores` is empty**, macOS may have SIP restrictions. Check:\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile        # shows the path pattern\n   sudo sysctl kern.coredump=1      # ensure dumps are enabled\n   ```\n\n4. **Reproduce the crash** — run your NativeAOT app; macOS will write a Mach-O core file to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n5. **Analyze with `lldb`** (since NativeAOT produces native binaries):\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n   Inside lldb: `bt` for backtrace, `thread list`, `frame variable`, etc.\n\n6. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS also writes `.ips` crash logs to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These contain a symbolic stack trace and can be a quick alternative to a full core dump.\n\n**Key point:** Since NativeAOT apps are fully native, you use the same OS-level (`lldb`, core files) tooling as any native C/C++ app — `createdump` (a CoreCLR tool) isn't needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bc2b9ce7-c829-4c00-a3d5-922a62ee0b3d","outputTokens":405,"requestId":"DA03:349D35:22ECEE1:26A7B91:6A03D8E5"},"id":"af5170a0-3ffb-459e-9d7a-64ed920e9822","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:50:39.801Z","parentId":"ebc3fe27-a1db-46ee-b642-24be34682093"}
